# Description of Implementation's Design and Intent

My implementation manages the heap as a sequence of variable-sized blocks, where each block has a
header and footer containing its size in units and allocation state.
In heapmgr1, free blocks are organized in a single doubly-linked free list using the header’s next
pointer and the footer’s prev pointer.
Heapmgr2 extends this idea by using multiple doubly-linked list, dividing free blocks into multiple
size-based bins to reduce search time for allocation, and to find a block that closely resembles the
size requested.
For allocation, heapmgr_malloc() first searches the free structure for a block large enough to
satisfy the request, reuses an existing free block when possible, and splits the block if it is
larger than needed so the remainder can stay available for future allocations. If no suitable free
block exists, the allocator expands the heap with sbrk().
For deallocation, heapmgr_free() marks the block as free, checks the physically adjacent lower and
upper neighbors using the boundary tags, and coalesces contiguous free blocks to reduce fragmentation.
I also included heap validity checking in debug mode so that the allocator verifies structural invariants
of the heap and free lists/bins at the entry and exit of heapmgr_malloc() and heapmgr_free().

